{{Infobox Governor | image = | |name= Hugo Cóccaro |order= |office= Governor of Tierra del Fuego |term_start= October 25, 2005 |term_end= December 10, 2007 |lieutenant= |predecessor= [[Jorge Colazo]] |successor= [[Fabiana Rios]] |birth_date= 1954 |birth_place= [[Saladillo, Buenos Aires|Saladillo]], [[Buenos Aires Province]] |profession= [[sawmill]] proprietor |party= [[Justicialist Party]] |footnotes= }}
'''Hugo Omar Cóccaro''' (born in 1954) is an [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[Justicialist Party]] (PJ) politician, former governor of [[Tierra del Fuego Province (Argentina)|Tierra del Fuego Province]] (formally Tierra del Fuego, Antarctica, and South Atlantic Islands).
Born in [[Saladillo, Buenos Aires|Saladillo]], [[Buenos Aires Province]], Cóccaro relocated to Tierra del Fuego at age 20 with his brother, with whom he started a construction firm.<ref name=monitor>[http://weblogs.clarin.com/elecciones-2007/archives/2007/06/un-bonaerense-un-chaqueno-y-una-rosarina-van-por-la-gobernacion-de.html ''Clarín: Monitor electoral] {{es icon}}</ref> He later purchased the San Justo Estancia, a [[Nothofagus pumilio|lenga beech]] sawmill near [[Río Grande, Tierra del Fuego|Río Grande]].<ref>[http://edant.clarin.com/diario/1998/04/13/e-06104d.htm ''Clarín''] {{es icon}}</ref> He had four daughters, and his marriage ended in separation.<ref name=monitor/><ref>[http://edant.clarin.com/diario/2007/06/20/elpais/p-01001.htm ''Clarín'': a río revuelto, ganancia de pescadores] {{es icon}}</ref>
Cóccaro entered politics in 2003, when he was elected vice-governor under Governor [[Jorge Colazo]] of the [[Radical Civic Union]] (UCR). He fell out with Colazo, however, and there were public rows between them. He became acting governor of Tierra del Fuego on October 25, 2005, when Colazo was suspended, and was confirmed in the post on December 2.
His tenure was marked for its failed support for RENASA, a provincial [[petroleum]] concern, and a subsequent [[impeachment]] attempt.<ref>[http://www.tiempofueguino.com.ar/cms/tiempofueguino_sp/ ''Tiempo Fuegino''] {{es icon}}</ref> Cóccaro ran for reelection in 2007, and won the first round; but he was defeated in the runoff by [[Fabiana Ríos]], the first woman to be elected governor in the history of Argentina. {{s-start}} {{succession box| title=[[List of Governors of Tierra del Fuego|Governor of Tierra del Fuego]]| before=[[Jorge Colazo]]| after=[[Fabiana Rios]]| years=2005&ndash;2007 | }} {{s-end}}
