{{main|United States foreign aid}}
The [[Federal government of the United States|United States government]] first recognized the usefulness of [[United States foreign aid|foreign aid]] as a tool of [[diplomacy]] in [[World War II]]. It was believed that it would promote liberal [[capitalist]] models of development in other countries and that it would enhance national security.<ref>{{Cite book|title= Foreign Aid |url= http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/foreign_aid.aspx| accessdate=2011-02-24}}</ref>
The [[United States]] is the largest contributor of military aid to foreign countries in the world, providing some form of assistance to over 150 countries each year.
==Military funding programs== {{citations needed|section|date=March 2016}} There are three main programs where military funding is allocated:
#[[United States Foreign Military Financing|Foreign military financing]] provides grants for the acquisition of U.S. defense equipment, services, and training. These grants enable friends and allies to improve their defense capabilities.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Foreign Military Financing Account Summary|url= https://www.state.gov/t/pm/ppa/sat/c14560.htm |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> The goals of FMF are: #:* Promoting national security by contributing to regional and global stability #:* Strengthening military support for democratically elected governments and containing transnational threats, including terrorism and trafficking in narcotics, weapons, and persons #:* Fostering closer military relationships between the U.S. and recipient nations #[[Peacekeeping Operations]] (PKO) provide voluntary support for international peacekeeping activities. These funds support non-U.N. operations and training in response to a nation’s crisis.<ref>{{Cite book|title= Foreign Aid: An Introductory Overview of U.S. Programs and Policy |url=https://fpc.state.gov/documents/organization/31987.pdf |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> The goals of PKO are: #:* Promoting increased involvement of regional organizations in conflict resolution #:* Helping leverage support for multinational efforts in the event of a nation's crisis #The [[International Military Education and Training]] program (IMET) offers military training on a grant basis to foreign military officials.<ref>{{Cite book|title= IMET Assessment Project 2007-2008 |url= http://www.ccmr.org/public/library_file_proxy.cfm/lid/5586 | accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> The goals of IMET are: #:* Encouraging effective defense relationships #:* Promoting interoperability with U.S. and coalition forces #:* Exposing foreign civilian and military officials to democratic values, military professionalism, and international norms of human rights
Some examples of this would include the United States' efforts in Colombia and South Korea. Military aid has been successful in stopping insurgency, providing stability, and ending conflicts within the region.{{cn|date=March 2016}}
In many other cases, military aid has laid the groundwork for other forms of aid. This aid includes building schools to promote education, providing clean drinking water, and further stabilizing food production. Without military aid, this development would have been impossible. {{cn|date=March 2016}}
Some may say that military aid is increasing insurgency in the area, but examples of French and United Nations' efforts show that it has been stopping terrorist forces; especially in Africa.{{cn|date=March 2016}}
==Criticisms==
Currently, Congress wants to cut defense spending by lowering the amount of aid given to foreign militaries.<ref name="news.yahoo.com">{{Cite book|title= Foreign Military Aid Needs to Be Cut, Not U.S. Military Spending|url= https://news.yahoo.com/s/ac/20110217/pl_ac/7883190_foreign_military_aid_needs_to_be_cut_not_us_military_spending| accessdate=2011-02-20}}</ref> Money saved from proposed cutbacks could benefit the U.S. military, which is closing military bases, freezing pay raises for service members, and cut the defense budget by $78 billion in 2011.<ref name="news.yahoo.com"/>
Particular targets of criticism include * Funds appropriated to the [[State Department]] and [[United States Department of Defense|Defense Department]] represent the vast majority of unclassified military aid and assistance. The public does not have any way of tracking classified programs administered by the U.S. intelligence community.<ref>{{Cite book|title= A Citizen’s Guide to Understanding U.S. Foreign Military Aid |url= http://projects.publicintegrity.org/militaryaid/default.aspx?act=faq| accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> * Foreign aid often aids the giver, not the recipient.{{cn|date=January 2015}} * Corruption is a major problem. Funds often go directly to leaders who may not share the aid with citizens.{{cn|date=January 2015}} * The United States gives the same amount of money to its top five aid recipients as they give to the rest of the world.<ref>Noah Grant{{Cite book|title= Just the Facts: Foreign Aid vs. Military Spending |url= http://www.yesmagazine.org/issues/a-just-foreign-policy/just-the-facts-foreign-aid-vs.-military-spending| accessdate=2011-02-24}}</ref> * Military aid went to [[Latin American]] dictatorships in the second half of the 20th century.{{cn|date=January 2015}}
